usually takes bus B to work,

00:00:02.816 --> 00:00:06.564
"but now she thinks that bus
A gets her to work faster.

00:00:06.564 --> 00:00:09.424
"She randomized 50 workdays
between a treatment group

00:00:09.424 --> 00:00:10.780
"and a control group.

00:00:10.780 --> 00:00:13.140
"For each day from the
treatment group, she took bus A;

00:00:13.140 --> 00:00:15.773
"and for each day from the
control group, she took bus B.

00:00:15.773 --> 00:00:19.513
"Each day she timed the
length of her drive."

00:00:19.513 --> 00:00:20.760
This is really interesting
what she did, it's very

00:00:20.760 --> 00:00:23.910
important, she randomized
the 50 work days.

00:00:23.910 --> 00:00:25.693
Before she did this, instead
of just kinda waking up in

00:00:25.693 --> 00:00:29.300
the morning and just deciding
on her own which bus to take.

00:00:29.300 --> 00:00:32.238
Because humans are infamously
bad at being random.

00:00:32.238 --> 00:00:33.565
Even when we think we're being random,

00:00:33.565 --> 00:00:35.017
we're actually not that random.

00:00:35.017 --> 00:00:38.686
She might inadvertently be
taking bus A earlier in the week.

00:00:38.686 --> 00:00:40.777
Or maybe the commute times are shorter.

00:00:40.777 --> 00:00:43.542
Or maybe she inadvertently
takes bus A when

00:00:43.542 --> 00:00:45.442
the weather is better,
when there's less traffic.

00:00:45.442 --> 00:00:49.089
Remember, there's a natural
tendency for human beings

00:00:49.089 --> 00:00:51.569
to want to confirm their hypothesis.

00:00:51.569 --> 00:00:54.089
So, if she thinks that
bus A is faster maybe

00:00:54.089 --> 00:00:56.865
she'll want to pick the days where she'll

00:00:56.865 --> 00:00:58.705
get data to confirm her hypothesis.

00:00:58.705 --> 00:01:01.940
